,Recommended,247240,7756666,"Posted: 25 November, 2013",all,McDuders,"One of my favorite games on the NES is Zelda II.  It had all the feelings of being a 2d fantasy sword-and-board platformer, where you can get into cool sword fights with skeletons, use magic, and do all kinds of cool moves.  Unfortunately, besides Battle of Olympus (eh...), there's not really any game that feels like Zelda II.  No game, that is, until Volgarr comes along, and shoves everything I love about Zelda II into one place, like being able to use your shield to block enemies, and using the down strike move.  I saw the trailers and some playthroughs of the first level, and I instantly fell in love.  Volgarr the Viking is the Zelda II I've been looking for.It's not just those things that make Volgarr such a great game.  All you have is a sword for close range attacks, and a spear for long-ranged attacks, and using it against a wall will give you many platforming possibilities.  Throughout the game are treasure chests, and hitting them twice will give you an item that will power-up Volgarr with a piece of armor or weapon.  More stuff out of these chests means more hit defense on your character (up to 3 hits), and getting a flame sword means doing more damage to enemies, so the game rewards you for doing well.And trust me, you'll need every piece of armor you can get.  It may not look like it from all of the trailers and gameplay videos, but this game is hard.  Regardless of your gaming experience, you will die.  A lot.  This isn't Candyland the game.  This isn't Seseme Street: Count with the Count.  This isn't Diablo III.  You will die.  Not only that, but each stage has a checkpoint only half-way though the game.  That means if you die on a boss, you go all the way back to the half-way point and have to do the rest of the stage plus the boss.  Is it frustrating?  Yes.  Is it teeth-grindingly difficult?  Yes.  Is it rewarding?  YOU BET YOUR SECOND-BORN SON IT IS.  You get exploding treasure when you beat a boss!  If that's not rewarding enough for you, than you need to see an optometrist.The way I see it, the game is not NES hard.  NES hard would be falling off a cliff because the game won't let you get a hit off of that supid bird.  NES hard would be getting knocked back and forth all over the place because the game thought it would be best to have 2 enemies side by side.  This is more SNES/Genesis hard, where it's tough as steel, but fair as a ref.  I see people play this game, and they get frustrated.  What's to be frustrated at?  It's not the game's fault you fell into those spikes: YOU jumped into them.  It's not the game's fault that you ran into those arrows: YOU didn't roll in time.  The game's fair but difficult challange gives me more of an incentive to complete it, because I feel like I'm not cheated when I play it.  I played the whole game.  I died a lot.  I never felt angry or frustrated the whole way through, becuase I knew the reason I keep dieing is because I didn't learn.In video games, what kills you makes you stronger.To conclude, I absolutely love this game.  It's the game I've been looking for for a long time.  I'm surprised people who are usually into hardcore games didn't this game a try.  This game has every bit of hardcore and more.  So, if you're into fun, fair, challenging platformers, give this a go.  The demo is a free download with barely any space holding it up, so what have you got to lose?This game will kick your♥♥♥♥♥ but not if you kick it first."
