,Recommended,247240,24549042,"Posted: 26 July, 2016",all,bluex44,"Tip: Take it slow. This is not a game you rush into. Be observant about what's coming up next.You'll swear that you remember this game from ""back in the day"" even though it wasn't around when you were a kid. This game is tough, but fair. You will have to memorize where the enemies are, their patterns, and how to defeat them, but not in a way that seems boring, unfair, or cheap. There is a genuine feeling of accomplishment when you figure out how to get through an area. Your deaths (there will be a lot of them) always feel like your fault, and not the fault of the programming. You would have lived if you would have pressed a button just a split second faster, timed a jump a bit better, or remembered to roll at just the right time. The controls are tight and responsive. If you remember the golden age of the Super Nintendo and Sega Genesis rivalry, you'll feel right at home here. It's tough, but rewarding. You might rage quit after failing to get through a section over and over, but you'll eventually come back to try again. I highly recommend trying Volgarr the Viking.A highlight is that there is no long, drawn out story. You start playing immediately. When you die there is no game over screen, you just start again at the last checkpoint. The ability to get into the gameplay so quickly makes this game perfect for picking up and playing when you have a free moment. There is no fluff between you and the action.NOTE: You CANNOT steer while jumping. Once you commit to a jump, you have to wait for it to play out. This was not a problem for me, I barely even noticed it, but many people can't adjust to this play style. You have been warned."
