,Not Recommended,247240,31455908,Posted: 29 April,all,Barzillai,"Volgarr is a hit or miss game. It has a lot of issue that leave it somewhere between good and bad. The controls feel...incomplete. Imagine fighting the bosses in megaman but megaman is a lead weight with only melee attacks. Volgarr doesn't have any momentum whatsoever. This is obviously intentional on the developers part but it wasn't ultimately necessary to make the game as ""brutally difficult"" as they intended. It is a difficult game but not because of good game design. It's difficult because you are essentially given unfair enemy placements and death traps and told to figure out a way. The game sort of ramps and wanes in difficulty with me having the most trouble on the fire level because of said instant death traps. The controls are so clunky that anything but perfection will leave you dead. Enemies have a fair amount of health with most things dying in a single hit and bosses taking around 10-15 hits to kill. Except for the bird boss. For some reason he takes around 20 hits. Even with fire sword, it just felt like he had way too much health. Coupled with a poorly designed room and difficult controls (especially while in the air) the game feels like it should have been tweaked a bit more. The sense of accomplishment you get from beating a boss is great so the game has that going for it but know that it can be prone to crashing when you defeat a boss. I'd heard of it but it only happened to me after defeating the bird boss. If you're looking for a game that is simply difficult, (I'd say this is up there with dark souls in terms of 1st playthrough difficulty) then Volgarr is for you. If you want a game that feels polished then steer clear. The graphics are SNES era 16-bit fair and the music is good but those don't help the game to get above a 6/10 from me."
