,Recommended,247240,8115438,"Posted: 19 December, 2013",all,Smiley,"This game captures the amazing nostaligic feeling of feeling absolutely crushed. If you are a very masochistic person who enjoys being repeatedly violated over and over again, I could not recommend this game enough. Volgar the Viking will make you question your life decisions. The control is tight, the level design is compact and intuitive, the enemy design and placement is creative, and Volgar's abilites are interesing and unique. However, a specific mechanic in this game can be either very fun for you or make you want to just uninstall this game and never look back. The fact that you will have to die so many times to learn patterns of enemies, where the pitfals are, how to defeat a certain part. It is an exercise in trial and error. That maybe what you want. But if you are looking at this game as a 'small little challange' then be forwarned, ""abandon all hope ye who enter here""."
,Recommended,247240,15630745,"Posted: 30 April, 2015",all,genoforprez,"Jump controls: garbageEverything else: excellentI have zero tolerance for the jump controls in this game, so I'm sending it to the graveyard, but I could potentially recommend it for its good points to anyone else who can handle the terrible jumping.--If you don't press a direction at the same time you press the jump button, you will only jump vertically instead of in the direction you are trying to go. This is made worse by the fact that, once your feet leave the ground, you have no control over your character in the air and just have to wait for them to fall wherever the trajectory takes them. This double strike gets very annoying, as the game demands quick reflexes and precision in both platforming and combat.Basically they are going for an old school Ghouls n' Ghosts type thing, but even as a person who grew up on those systems, I can't claim to have much nostalgia for the bad aspects of those games. I mean, I enjoyed Ghouls n' Ghosts and still do, but that game doesn't demand precision out of you right away, does not require you to rote memorize the layout of the level, and has waaaaay more checkpoints.I don't want to give it a thumbs down, because I realize the controls are kind of an homage, and everything else about the game is quite good, but damn. I just hate the platforming."
