76561198067703112,Not Recommended,247240,18944711,"Posted: 7 November, 2015",all,ARCWuLF,"CASUAL GAMERS NEED NOT APPLYIf you likebeing kicked in the ballsplaying a really difficult game (and we're talkingSuper Ghouls & Ghostsdifficult), then this is the game for you!No health bar, cumbersome control, lots of cheap hits, and enemies that can move faster than your character are the name of the game here. It isbrutallydifficult, and I have to say that it isn't to the game's credit.Retro gamers will be reminded of the gameRastan, in that in both games you control a barbarian-type character who attacks with a sword while (mostly) walking to the right. But whereasRastanis a game that you can learn from,Volgarr the Vikingisn't. This is mostly due to the fact that when you die, you go back to the last checkpoint, and checkpoints in this game are few and far between. Your character starts with a sword for his main attack, a spear for distance attacks and for climbing up walls, and a shield for defense, which can deflect some projectiles and that you lose after taking a single hit. If you're lucky, you can find a treasure chest that will first upgrade your shield (I have no idea what this does because you lose the upgraded shield after one hit -- it doesn't go back to the normal shield, mind you, it just goes away like the regular shield), then upgrade you to a helmet (that will take an additional hit, bringing your hit points up to two, after which you die), and a flaming sword that I presume increases your attacks (I don't know because I lost the flaming sword every single time after I got it on single-hit enemies).The graphics are pleasant to look at in a 90s arcade sort of way, and the sound is certainly up to par with titles in that vein, but that's about all I can say in its favor.Now, I'm occasionally up for a side-scrolling platforming challenge: I've beatenSuper The Empire Strikes Backon the SNES, every version ofBionic Commandoon every system it was ever made for,Strideron the Sega Genesis and quite a few of the NESMega Mangames. Maybe it's my old age setting in, or maybe I'm just tired of developer B.S., but I'm really starting the hate the kind of cheap, artificial challenge some of these modern platformers are offering by making the game so unforgiving. I've played the game for about two hours, and I've only ever gotten to the second checkpoint (not even the end of the first stage, if there are more stages). Oh yeah, and you have to start the game from the beginning every single time you quit the game and restart, so you'd better get good at those first few areas. I was really looking forward to this game and now I'm just angry that I've purchased it.If masochism and self-mutilation are your thing, then by all means: Go for it! Anyone who just wants to play a fun, challenging platform game can spend their money onSpelunky, Shovel Knight, Axiom Verge,or any of the dozens of other titles on Steam that are more rewarding, more forgiving, and certainly more fun."
