76561198215878617,Not Recommended,247240,29613487,Posted: 31 January,all,Wasdukannst,"This game is too easy.It is marketed as a good, difficult retro platformer with tight controls,as well as having a healthy dose of viking violence.Of those promised qualities, it delivered only in regards to viking violence,since it is neither good, nor difficult and the controls are decent at best.While this game has a lot of minor issues, I want to focus onwhat I perceive to be the root of all evil when it comes to this game:It's approach to difficulty and leveldesign.Difficulty in VolgarrHaving played through the first three levels of Volgarrand beaten what most players seem to consider this game's hardest boss on the way,I can honestly say that no single combat encounter, jump or platforming puzzlewas even remotely close to being hard to pull off or figure out.Why then have I not completed more of the game in the time that I played it?Because checkpoints are so rare that you need to get past just about a millionof those obstacles in order to reach one checkpoint.This makes Volgarr feel and play like a game of low to medium difficulty,that has had about 50-80% of it's checkpoints removed.This is not how you challenge players.It's how you make them bored out of their mind.Having to run through the motions ploughing through mindnumbingly boringand repetitive combat encounters, just to fail and die at the boss,is neither challenging, nor is it fun.It is aggravating and a waste of time.I just had a glance at the kickstarter page and last time I checked,an ""insane"" boss in a game for the ""truly hardcore"" took more than a couple of tries to beat.While I have beaten some hard games before, I am by no means just that good at video games.This game almost exclusively tests your patience rather than your skill.If you are into that fair enough, but I'm not.Leveldesign in VolgarrFrom what I can tell, there are 3 ways of trivialising pretty much all enemies in the game:-Crouch and slash with your sword.-Kill them from a safe distance using spears.-Make them seperate from their pack and come to you by using spears.That approach to enemy-placement may or may not be retro, that is for others to decide.What I do know is that it is boring, unimaginative, and repetitive.Enemy design is equally bad:With few exceptions, there are basically enemies that will jump at youand enemies that slowly lumber towards you.Both can only damage you by touching you.Needless to say, neither of them are challenging, fun, or interesting.By now you should be able to guess what I think about the platforming and puzzles,so I won't go into detail but instead confirm your suspicion: I strongly dislike them.ConclusionToday I read an old forum post of one of the developers statingthat he wanted a game that played exactly like the games of oldrather than like a retro game with modern influences.That at least makes some amount of sense and explains,why the developers apparently refused to learn from more modern,but actually challenging games like ""they bleed pixels"",which released before volgarr and is vastly superior in every aspect.Avoid Volgarr and get ""they bleed pixels"" and/or ""Wings of Vi"" instead."
