76561197966772921,Recommended,247240,18931562,"Posted: 7 November, 2015",all,Groo,"SpoilersI have done my best to keep this review from spoilers so that readers can enjoy it without regretting reading it. As with food though, there might be some traces of ""allergens"".My experience of older gamesI grew up playing the Sega Master System, Sega Mega Drive, Super Nintendo (SNES), and Game Boy (first generation). I found it appropriate for me to write my first review on this particular game since it belongs to a genre that I hold very dear. The SNES console is my all time favourite game system.GraphicsVölgarr truly captures the feeling and aestethics of games of the past! People who have played a game called Rastan seem to recognise elements from that game and while I never played it, based on pictures on Google I see why. The enemies and levels are clearly inspired from that game.The graphics remind me, however, of another game which I think Völgarr resembles at least as much: ActRaiser II. This game was released on the SNES console and Völgarr's graphics are defenitely 16-bit. The character's poses, movement and moves and also the music and variance in level themes resemble in a way those in ActRaiser II.One thing that reveals Völgarr is a modern game is the background/the horizon which has been blurred to give a sence of depth. While the purpouse is obvious, I have never seen that in a 16-bit game and would have preferred graphics limited to the style of the time. Sence of depth was very well achieved in the old games too, but one pixel was one pixel and could never be blurred.GameplayThis game could easily have been published back in the early 90's. The character moves just like in a viking/swordsman/fantasy themed SNES-game: Relatively slowly, giving a sence of weight (muscles, armor, weapons and muscels). The attack moves are slightly delayed and need to be perfectly timed just like in the old games (if you remember games like Altered Beast you know timing is everything!)The controls are 2 buttons + arrows / 4 buttons + arrows depending on how you choose to play. if you want one button for each action, you go with 4. I chose to go with 2, which means e.g. that throwing a spear = UP + ACTION.Let's just lean back for a moment and enjoy the nostalgia...Right, let's continue!One of the main themes the developers advertise in the game trailer is dying. All of us who played NES, SNES, Game Boy, Sega Master System or Sega Mega Drive games know what it feels like to fail over and over and over again. It was so frustrating, yet addictive. You HAD to beat that level and you HAD to figure out what series of moves and attacks the boss had in order to beat him/her. Völgarr captures this beautifully! Just getting through the first level/world and beat the boss feels like conquering the world! (The developers of Völgarr have been kind though - back in the days you had often limited lives, limited ""Continues"", and sometimes no checkpoints at all!)After a while, when you decide to play the game all over again, you suddenly realise how good you've gotten at this game. You're wielding your sword and throwing spears as if you were born doing so. That moment made me smile - it really brings back memories...My thoughts (who am I kidding - you know what I'm gonna say!)I LOVE THIS GAME and anyone who grew up with or has ever happened to fall in love with 16-bit games in particular will too! I began this review feeling quite sophisticated but after writing this and realising how much I really like this game, I end up feeling like a kid on saturday morning - waiting for my best friend to come over for a sleepover with snacks and video games all night!I really have to try to fix my SNES console (showing black sreen of death)..."
