,Recommended,247240,8028245,"Posted: 13 December, 2013",all,MegaSeveN,"This is definitely a game made for a small audience, and I'm super grateful to the developers for making it. You only ever have two weapons: a sword and a throwing spear. The sword can be used in a few ways and upgraded to a fire version (if you're good enough), but the real star of the show is the spear. Not only can it be used to attack enemies from afar (infinitely), but it can also be used to make platforms to stand on by throwing them at walls. And that's not just a fun gimmick... there are numerous chests out of reach through normal means until you find clever ways to throw spears and make paths to them.That's also how much of the battles unfold. It's not really a good idea to charge ahead and hope for the best so much as learn how enemies attack and make deliberate movements in order to vanquish them. The bosses work the same way too. Believe me, you'll die plenty of times fighting them, but each death helps you learn their pattern and once you know it, you can bring them down without taking a hit. Thank goodness for unlimited lives, eh?Just in case it isn't hard enough, there's actually a harder alternate version of each stage (with limited lives) that you can only get to by playing the previous stage near-flawlessly. And the only way to get the best ending is to do that for every stage.If you miss the good ol' days of fair but unrelenting difficulty, pick this sucker up."
,Recommended,247240,8101237,"Posted: 18 December, 2013",all,Riisoz,"Fantastically difficult in a Super Meat Boy kind of way. Good time waster if you have the patience to keep playing after a really BS death. Possibly a good game to play while in queue on League of Legends or any downtime during another game.Other games that fit this genre of 'games to play while you play other games' would probably be: Super Meat Boy, Binding Of Isaac, Hotline Miami, Rogue Legacy.I haven't played much but if this were my type of game (as is the case with many friends of mine), I could see it being very fun to attempt to do the same thing but faster, smoother, or more carefully. Again, if you have the patience and like games that you are most likely going to have to keep playing doing the same thing over and over again to progress you will probably like this game.Recommend a Controller7-8/10"
,Recommended,247240,2064734,"Posted: 16 September, 2013",all,DuckyBread,"Goddamn, this game is tougher than a pot of boiled ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥s!BUT IN A GOOD WAY, HONEST!It truly does live up to the claim of being hard like the games of the past. It's tons of pattern and level memorization, and always remembering what powers are at your disposal.The game is unforgiving, but does not ONCE treat the player like they're stupid. The game KNOWS you're smart and challenges you to prove it through tough enemy, trap, and obstacle placement. There's tons of trail and error, so be prepared to restart a board many a time until you know it like the back of your hand.That said though, the boards can be quite lengthy, which makes the fact that you have to clear them on one life a bit of a chore (given you have to restart from the beginning every death). That's one complaint: no mid-way checkpoints. But I suppose that's something modern games have spoiled us with. So not really a complaint, more like a ""UGHHH MODERN GAMING WHHHY"" point.Although I do have a legitimate complaint: The controls. I've been playing with a 360 pad which is a no brainer for me given this is a side scrolling platform which, in my books, demands the precision. Now, having said that, I find the controls while responsive and good, can also be pretty clunky. Does that make sense? No? Well lemme try and explain.You basically work on 3 inputs, A, X and your joystick (d-pad). A jumps, X attacks, and your joystick moves. Simple right? Well, holding up on the joystick draws your spear, and then pressing X throws said spear (and with later power ups, holding up for an extended period powers your throw). I'm not sure if it affects play or not, but sometimes while jumping, I'll hold up and draw my spear, which often gets me killed. I'm not sure if it adjusts the player's hit box while doing so, but I'm going to say it does for the sake of my argument, although it may turn out I'm just crap.Second point: You have 2 jumps. A standard leap, and pressing jump once again while in a jump will cause you to spin your sword and perform a double jump. Pretty standard fare, right?Well, if you just plain press jump, you'll jump straight up and be unable to move, but if you move and jump, you're committed to your jump arch (think original Castlevania style). So, ok, not so bad right?This is where things get UUGHGHHHH.If you are in mid jump arch and double jump without holding the intended direction you want to go in, your second jump CANCELS your jump arch.Now I know WHY they did it, for more precise platforming, but it can really mess you up if you don't anticipate the game. And one slip up means you can be toast and have to start all over again. It's a bit frustrating.GOOD POINTS THOUGH!The simplistic controls take getting used to, but they can be mastered easily since there isn't a whole lot of complexity to them (besides what I listed above). And while restarting a level is a pain, the pixel art is soooo gorgeous and the animations are so smooth and nice that it eases that pain a bit.As well, the game does a great job of building avatar strength through the power up system, and the best example of this is through the spears.Just plain Jane, you can throw a basic spear and more often than not, it'll kill an enemy in one hit and destroy itself. A second upgrade will give you a shield that can block up to two hits. Now this third upgrade gives you a slightly cooler looking shield AND powers up your spear. How does this affect your spear? Well now you can ♥♥♥♥ING PIN GUYS TO WALLS! It's so bad♥♥♥♥♥ let me tell you. If you can nail a line of enemies with a fully charged spear, nothing screams satisfaction like watching them all get sent flying by your man-missile. Upgrades beyond this add additional hit points to the player, and eventually a fire spraying sword.In short, if you're looking for a classic feeling game with a steep (but rewarding) challenge, pick it up!If you're looking for something a bit more relaxed, you may want to look else where.I give Volgarr an 8 out of 10!"
