76561198047699332,Recommended,247240,9671401,"Posted: 29 March, 2014",all,BrettH,"It's a Solid, difficult gameMost of the difficulty comes from the very mechanical mechanics, there are locked jump arcs, 1 checkpoint/level, passive shields with incomplete coverage (chest but not legs or head), your damage, enemy damage, and health can all be counted in very basic integers, enemy ""AI"" is on the level of Mario 1, and insta-death pits are plentiful. If you want to do well you have to control Volgarr like you are operating a toy car, or crane, not like an organic human we're use to in games.The level design is mostly excellent*, generally letting you see possible threats before it's too late**, and requiring full use of your abilities. Every enemy feels different and needs to be aproached differently and the game ensures every encounter or obstical is unique from all others.The game does spike in difficulty beyond the first level, mainly due to spawning enemies faster, and with less forewarning (from the side of the screen, from patches of water, or from the ground as opposed to crawling up the screen).The game has been compared to Dark Souls, as it features a similar experience of adversity --> mastery. Personally, though I love both, I find Volgarr more consistant, and faster, but if you prefer a focus on watching for tells, and learning how enemies act/react you'll enjoy DS over Volgarr's attempt at purity in execution.*The very last alternate level though is a pain in the♥♥♥♥♥ it has several unreliable spawns of fast flying enemies that not only hurt you but knock you around during the toughest platforming in the game. I have lost many 0 death runs to that level, thankfully it's short.**The game has an option to zoom out the camera, you have to toggle it in the options then hit space in game, this shoud be the default zoom, as it is just slightly larger than the enemies trigger distance, the game is unfair without it."
